narratives.question_text: What is the name of your TA?
Use the space below to comment on questions 1-10, if you wish
comments: This course is the lab meeting for Michael Dove's doctoral students (and affiliates), so many of these questions don't apply. It's not taught as a regular course, but rather as a seminar in which we present and discuss our own research. In this sense, it's an excellent course, but not taught as other courases are.
The chance to interact with other students at different stages of their PhDs and share our research.

-perhaps the single most valuable resource at Yale for me.-open forum feedback from professor-ability to practice presentation skills-get feedback on wide range of pressing questions from talented group of individuals with distinct but related specialties at different stages of doctoral program.
This doctoral lab is extremely helpful as a sounding ground for my own work and to connect with and intellectually engage others in my field.

narratives.question_text: The things about this course most in need of improvement are:
comments: Nothing, really - the course works exceedingly well as-is.

I enjoyed having some time for general discussions or guidelines, like we did earlier with the discussion led by Dana on quals or about writing up, and like we are proposing to do with NSF proposals. We should keep these and maybe add more time for these types of discussions.

narratives.question_text: What was the availability and quality of help you received of the instructor and TA?
Discuss if you wish how this course fits into your overall program.
comments: directly related as it is forum to present on current stage of work: funding proposals, potential publications, fieldwork, dissertation chapter drafts, practice jobtalks.

Very useful part of program, since it facilitates my ability to look forward to the future work and expectations of the doctoral program, and strengthen peer mentorships and friendships in the process.
